  "prompt": "What is the stock purchase plan for Tesla motors?",
  "response": "A stock purchase plan for a company like Tesla typically refers to an Employee Stock Purchase Plan (ESPP). While specific details may vary, an ESPP generally allows employees to purchase company stock at a discounted price through payroll deductions over a specified offering period.\n\nKey components of Tesla's ESPP (if available) might include:\n\n1. **Eligibility:** Generally, employees must meet certain criteria such as length of employment to participate in the ESPP.\n2. **Enrollment Periods:** Specific windows during which employees can sign up for the plan.\n3. **Offering Periods:** Time frames during which employee contributions are collected. These can be typically every six months.\n4. **Contribution Limits:** Employees can usually contribute a percentage of their salary, often capped at a certain amount per year.\n5. **Purchase Discount:** Stocks are purchased at a discount to the market price, typically ranging from 10% to 15%.\n6. **Look-back Provision:** Some plans may include a \"look-back\" feature allowing the purchase price to be based on the stock's price at the beginning of the offering period or the end, whichever is lower.\n7. **Tax Implications:** ESPPs often offer favorable tax treatment under Section 423 of the Internal Revenue Code.\n\nFor exact details on Tesla's latest stock purchase plan offerings, one would need to check Tesla's official filings, such as the prospectus found through investor relations or contact the company's HR department.",
